Title : Robert Shirley, 7th Earl Ferrers
Text : '''Robert Shirley, 7th Earl Ferrers''' [[Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (21 September 1756 –  2 May 1827), styled '''Viscount Tamworth''' from 1778 to 1787, was a British nobleman.

The eldest son of [[Robert Shirley, 6th Earl Ferrers|Robert Shirley]], he became a [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy]] [[viscount]] after his father succeeded his brother in the earldom in 1778. On 4 July 1781, both Ferrers and Tamworth were appointed [[deputy lieutenant]]s for [[Derbyshire]]. He succeeded his father in the earldom in 1787.<ref name="doyle">{{cite book | last=Doyle | first=James William Edmund | authorlink=James William Edmund Doyle | title=The Official Baronage of England | volume=1 | place=London | publisher=Longmans, Green | year=1886 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B-kIAAAAIAAJ | page=743}}</ref>

Ferrers was named a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]] in 1788,<ref name="doyle" /> and was much interested in genealogy.<ref name="stemmata" />

Robert married Elizabeth Prentiss (d. 14 September 1799) on 13 March 1778 at [[St Leonard's, Shoreditch]]. They had one son:<ref name="stemmata">{{cite book | title=Stemmata Shirleiana | first=Evelyn Philip | last=Shirley | authorlink=Evelyn Shirley (1812–1882) | publisher=Nichols and Sons | location=Westminster | year=1873 | pages=201–202 | url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924029787250}}</ref>
*Robert Sewallis Shirley, Viscount Tamworth (9 November 1778 – 6 June 1824), married on 5 August 1800 to Hon. Sophia Caroline Curzon, daughter of [[Nathaniel Curzon, 2nd Baron Scarsdale]], without legitimate issue; left a natural daughter, [[Caroline Shirley, Duchess Sforza Cesarini|Caroline]] (1818–1897). He purchased a commission as cornet and sub-lieutenant in the [[2nd Regiment of Life Guards]] on 6 October 1798,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15067|page=934|date=2 October 1798}}</ref> was promoted into the [[Grenadier Guards|1st Regiment of Foot Guards]] as a lieutenant on 4 November 1800,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15307|page=1242|date=1 November 1800}}</ref> and retired from the Army in January 1802.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15444|page=46|date=12 January 1802}}</ref> He was commissioned major of the Derby Regiment of Volunteer Infantry (militia) on 26 April 1804.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15855|page=1330|date=26 October 1805}}</ref>

He married his second wife, Elizabeth Mundy (d. 22 February 1827), daughter of [[Wrightson Mundy]], on 28 September 1799, by whom he left no issue.<ref name="stemmata" /> Since his son predeceased him, he was succeeded by his brother [[Washington Shirley, 8th Earl Ferrers|Washington]] when he died at [[Hastings]] in 1827.<ref name="doyle" /> The Earl and his second wife were both buried at [[Breedon on the Hill]]. He left the family estates at [[Ragdale, Leicestershire|Ragdale]] and [[Ratcliffe on the Wreake]], [[Leicestershire]], which had descended from the Basset family, to his granddaughter Caroline, later Duchess Sforza Cesarini.<ref name="stemmata" />

